# Mechanisms of weathering:

3 Primary types
- Physical weathering
- Biological weathering
- Chemical weathering


## Physical Weathering:

### Frost Wedging
- Weathering caused by the expansion of water as it freezes
	- Expands by approximately 9%, based on density difference



### Thermal Expansion
- AKA Spalling
- Weathering that occurs when the outer layer of rock heats up but the inside stays cooler
	- This causes uneven expansion
	- ...which causes the surface to peel and flake off
- Very slow process
- Typically occurs in
	- Deserts



### Salt Crystal Growth
- AKA Haloclasty
- Weathering that occurs when saltwater seeps into fractures in rocks, then crystallizes
	- This causes the salt contained in it to crystallize
	- ..which can create dimples in the surface of the rock
		- Why it's AKA "Honeycomb wedging"
- Occurs within and around:
	- Coastal environments
	- Desert environments


### Unloading
- AKA Exfoliation and Sheeting
 - Occurs when the confining pressure above a pluton is released, forcing it to move upwards and surface rocks to spread apart

## Chemical weathering
- The weakening of rock by chemical forces
	- Almost always relies on water and dissolved acids
		- IE carbonic acid
- 3 Main types:

[[Unsorted/Weathering#^aaa\|Weathering#^aaa]]

### Dissolution
> [!Dissolution]+
> Minerals in rocks are dissolved by water
^aaa
- Minerals in rocks are dissolved by water
	- Minerals can be re-crystallized via precipitation when the water evaporates
- Ions are extracted from the surface of rocks and carried away to net sediment
- Dissolved ions accumulate in the cracks between grains of sediment
	- Cements them together, critical to formation of [[Unsorted/Sedimentary rocks\|Sedimentary rocks]]

###### Cave formation
- Caves grow due to deposition from dissolved minerals
	- Happens in chemically-sensitive rocks like limestone or halite
		- Limestone is typically dissolved by carbonic acid
	- Acidic waters are required for this process

### Oxidation
- Occurs when extra electrons are stripped away from the surface of a rock
	- Mafic (Ferromagnesian) silicates are most susceptible
- Can result in colorful stains on rock surfaces
- Banded iron: ![Pasted image 20221006134512.png](data:image/png;base64,) 



### Hydrolysis
- Porassium (K+) ions are replaced by Hydrogen (H+) ions
	- Converts potassium feldspar into Kaolinite (clay)
		- Most common type of weathering for feldspars


## Spheroidal weathering
- All forms of weathering tend to form rocks into more spherical shapes
	- Because corners are much more vulnerable to weathering
- Can be done by water, wind, or ice
![Pasted image 20221006135104.png](data:image/png;base64,)



# Rates of weathering
- Depends on...
	- Mineral composition
		- Softer minerals like feldspar erode quickly
			- Also Halite, more susceptible to chemical weathering
		- Harder minerals like quartz erode slowly
			- One of the reasons so much sand is made of quartz
		- Examples:
			- Softer headstone materials will erode faster
	- ...[[Unsorted/Climate\|Climate]]
		- Temperature and precipitation
		- Chemical weathering:
			- Warm and wet climates
				- Warm climates cause faster chemical reactions
				- Places with active [[Unsorted/The Water Cycle\|Hydrospheres]] are exposed to more fresh water
					- Harder for water to get saturated
		- Physical weathering
			- Drier and cooler climates
				- Dry climates have very little chemical weathering


### Differential weathering
- Rocks of different composition weather differently
	- Results in many of the most exotic rock formations


### Positive feedback cycle of weathering
- Physical weathering increases surface area
- ...which vastly increases the rate of chemical weathering
- ...and makes the rock easier to physically weather
